Convolutional Neural Network¶

In [ ]:
i=Input((img_height,img_width,img_channel))
x=Conv2D(32,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(i)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=Conv2D(32,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(x)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=MaxPooling2D((2,2))(x)

x=Conv2D(64,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(x)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=Conv2D(64,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(x)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=MaxPooling2D((2,2))(x)

x=Conv2D(128,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(x)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=Conv2D(128,(3,3),activation='relu',padding='same')(x)
x=BatchNormalization()(x)
x=GlobalMaxPooling2D()(x)
x=Dropout(0.2)(x)
x=Flatten()(x)
x=Dense(2056,activation='relu')(x)
x=Dropout(0.2)(x)
x=Dense(2,activation='softmax')(x)

model=Model(i,x)
model.summary()

The first model I created is a Convolutional Neural Network.

The first layer is a convolution layer with 32 kernels of size 3X3. Also, the input layer has the size of 350x350x3 in order to make all the input images have an equal size. The final layer has 4114 parameters.

Model Optimization Technique¶

Image Data Generator¶

An image data generator was then created on the train and validation data which would allow me augment the images in real-time during training of the model. This would improve on the robustness of the model as various transformations of the training image is used for model building.

The transformations done on the training images include:

  1. Rotation of the axis
  2. Normalization of the image pixel values
  3. Zooming the images
  4. Flipping the images
  5. Adjusting of the brightness

Image Data Generator for Train data¶

In [25]:
train_data_generator=tf.keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=20,rescale=1/255,width_shift_range=0.1,
                                                                     height_shift_range=0.1,shear_range= 0.1,zoom_range=0.2,brightness_range = (0.1, 0.9),horizontal_flip=True)

train_data=train_data_generator.flow_from_dataframe(train,train_path,x_col='filename',y_col='category',

The model was then fitted using the train data, and the validation data was also being used to assess the accuracy of the model at each run. The total number of epoch set was 50. However, to avoid overfitting issues, an early stop criteria was defined. The early stop criteria is the validation_loss, so if the validation loss cannot be improved on after 2 trials, the model would stop fitting.

Using the CNN model, I then predicted the images on the test data. As the predicted values are probabilities, I then got the class by taking the class with the highest probability

In conclusion, this assignment looks at using 2 different models to classify images as either cat or dogs. One of the challenges of this task was fitting my models and trying to optimize the model as the models took a long time to run and I also encountered crashes sometimes becuase the ram was used up.
